text:
In 1830, a man named Charles Goodyear sat alone in a prison cell—not because he committed a crime, but because he couldn’t pay his debts. The world saw him as a failure. But Charles saw something else: possibility.
He had become obsessed with a strange, messy substance—natural rubber. At the time, it was nearly useless. It melted in summer, cracked in winter, and couldn’t be trusted for anything important. But Charles believed it could be more.
Even behind bars, he kept experimenting. With borrowed tools and scraps, he worked day and night. In 1839, after countless failures, he accidentally spilled a rubber-sulfur mixture near a hot stove. The result? Vulcanized rubber—flexible, durable, and weatherproof. For the first time, rubber could be used in shoes, machines, and eventually… tires.
He patented the process in 1844, but instead of fortune, he faced copycats and courtroom battles. He lost money. His wife Clarissa died. His children lived in hardship. Still, he kept going.
Charles Goodyear died in 1860—sick, broke, and largely forgotten.
But his invention outlived him.
In 1898, a businessman named Frank Seiberling founded a tire company—and named it Goodyear, in honor of the man who made the modern rubber industry possible.
Charles never saw it. He never made a fortune. But every car, every tire, every road that hums beneath our feet owes something to the man who refused to quit.
Sometimes, greatness isn't rewarded in a lifetime.
Sometimes, it’s what we leave behind that changes everything.

replies.reply_text: @RetiredNow 2 winters ago I remember learning that Mosgiel has a -5, as one of friends lives there, and there was a cluster of frosts recorded around the South Island. I am very sensitive to how winters go from year to year, as I am most comfortable waking up to a 7-8 in my loft with no heat, really appreciated the warmth of my modest blanket collection, until I get out of bed, pop on my robe, sit at my desk, and run my air conditioner at 25, or more for half an hour or more then drop it to 17 until I feel that the lot is warm enough to last, and cold rainy mornings are different to frosty mornings. Our frosts have barely scratched the surface where we live , half way across the east in Christ Church. Ones who feel the cold don't feel a difference like I do. We had 2 days where it hit 17 briefly, not long after the solstice, and Saturday is forecast to be 15, so far, with maybe a couple of 13s. We are basically already halfway through winter now.

@RetiredNow I kept bees for a while, and since I was in a neighborhood, I built a solid 8ft high privacy fence around them. What I learned from that is that bees make a beeline in 3D space. If they come out of their nest area at 8ft high, they travel at 8ft high until they get where they are going. Which was good for my neighbors.

text: Good morning from Western Australia. The day dawned very cool for us. In the 25 years we have lived in this area we have only ever had one 3 day period where there was frost on the ground, and that was only minus 1C, so not cold by US standards but cold for ours. Most people here don't dress for the cold, or even very cool weather, that is 1-8C first thing in the morning. Me? No problem I spent a good part of my life in southern NZ where winter could get to minus 6C or lower in some places. Again, not cold by central US or Canadian standards, but enough to need 3 layers of wool clothes if you were going to be outside.

Bastards Yes, the American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) recently filed a lawsuit against Robert F. Kennedy Jr., Secretary of Health and Human Services (HHS), over changes to federal vaccine policy
.
The lawsuit, filed on July 7, 2025, alleges that Kennedy unlawfully and unilaterally changed COVID-19 vaccine recommendations by removing the vaccine from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's (CDC) recommended immunization schedule for healthy children and pregnant women. The AAP and other medical organizations argue that this decision was not based on science and violated federal procedures, particularly concerning the role of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices (ACIP). They also claim these actions are undermining vaccine infrastructure and potentially increasing vaccine hesitancy.
The lawsuit seeks to reverse these policy changes and restore the COVID-19 vaccine recommendations for pregnant women and healthy children aged six months to 17 years.
